@NODE sharedport "Shared IDCMP Port"

IE can generate a source code in which more than one window use  the  same
IDCMP port.

That can be useful for several reasong, among which  these  are  the  most
important:

- all the windows can be used at  the  same  time (like  the  DriPens  and
  Screen Tags requesters in IEditor)

- your GUI will require less memory

- you save some signals bit (a task can't have more than  16  signals:  in
  fact IEditor uses a shared port in  the  editing  windows  and  in  some
  requesters; therefore you can open as many windows as you like)


In order to handle the shared port, the C.generator uses this method:

- the HandleIDCMPPort() function is similar to the  Handle<Wnd>IDCMP()
  ones: it just handles more than one window.

- when a message arrives at the IDCMP port, HandleIDCMPPort() copy its
  content in the IDCMPMsg structure and  then  it  calls  the  routine
  which is pointed by the ExtData field of the windows from where  the
  message came.


Here's an example to explain better how to use it:


BOOL  running = TRUE;

void main( void )
{
    /*  insert here the initialization stuff... ;-)  */

    OpenMainWindow();   /* since this is just an example I don't do */
    OpenToolsWindow();  /* any check on return codes.  Instead, you */
                        /* MUST always check the return codes!      */

    MainWnd->ExtData = HandleMain;
    MainWnd->ExtData = HandleToolsIDCMP;

    /*  Main Loop  */

    while( running ) {

        WaitPort( IDCMPPort );

        HandleIDCMPPort();
    }

    CloseToolsWindow();
    CloseMainWindow();
}

void HandleMain( void )
{
    if(!( HandleMainIDCMP() ))
        running = FALSE;
}


...wasn't it too much hard, is it? ;-)
@ENDNODE

